<section class="xm-glossary-section">
  <details class="xm-glossary-details">
    <summary class="xm-glossary-summary">Glossary — Key Terms<span class="xm-chevron">+</span></summary>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Janus</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Roman two-faced god of doors, gates, beginnings, and transitions. The first month of the Gregorian calendar (January / Latin <em>Ianuarius</em>) is named for him. His theological role as "the door" is directly displaced by Yahushua's claim in John 10:9.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Aviv</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The first month of Yahuah's year (Exodus 12:2; Devarim 16:1), fixed by the renewed moon, the rising of Spica, and the ripening of barley in the land of Yisrael. Falls in what the Gregorian calendar calls late March or April. The Gregorian January 1 replaces Aviv as the calendar year's start.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Calendae (the Calends)</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The Roman religious term for the first day of every month — derived from the public "calling out" (Latin <em>calare</em>) of the month's festivals. The Calends of January was the major Roman New Year festival, dedicated to Janus, featuring strenae (gift exchanges) and vota (vows to the gods).</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Strenae</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Roman ceremonial New Year's gifts exchanged on the Calends of January in honor of Janus. The direct ancestor of the modern New Year's gift custom (French <em>étrennes</em>, Italian <em>strenna</em>). Originally included symbolic items like laurel branches, honey-dates, and coins bearing Janus's image.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Vota</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Roman religious vows taken publicly to specific deities at significant calendar moments, including the Calends of January. The direct ancestor of the modern New Year's resolution. Originally binding under religious sanction; modern resolutions are the same structure with the deity invoked removed.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Julian Calendar</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The Roman calendar reform of Julius Caesar (45 BC) that fixed the year at 365.25 days, moved the year's start to January 1, and named the months in their modern arrangement (mostly after Roman gods or emperors). The predecessor to the Gregorian reform.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Gregorian Calendar</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The Roman papal calendar reform of Pope Gregory XIII (1582 AD), commissioned to fix the Easter date by recalibrating to the spring equinox. The modern Western calendar in universal use. Sun-cult solar in foundation, papal in authority, named for Gregory.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Saint Sylvester I (314–335 AD)</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Roman pope during Constantine's reign. His death day (December 31) is the Catholic feast of Saint Sylvester, fused with the secular New Year's Eve in much of Catholic Europe (German <em>Silvesterabend</em>). The Catholic label laid over the Roman year-end festival.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Akitu</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The Babylonian twelve-day New Year festival, held in late March around Aviv, featuring public vows to the gods, the king's renewal of his mandate, and the ritual re-establishment of the cosmos. The direct ancestor of the New Year's resolution practice.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Hogmanay</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The Scottish name for New Year's Eve, derived from older Celtic and possibly Norse-derived folk traditions. Preserves the First Footing divination ritual (item #14) and the "Auld Lang Syne" remembering-song (item #10).</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">First Footing</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Scottish/Northern English threshold-magic ritual in which the first person to cross the household's threshold after midnight on January 1 determines the year's fortune. Divinatory in form; tall dark-haired men carrying coal, shortbread, salt, and whisky are the prescribed first-footer.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Aion / Chronos</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Greek personifications of time. Chronos (older, time-as-passage, depicted as old bearded man with scythe — the source of "Father Time"). Aion (younger, time-as-age, depicted as youthful figure — the source of "Baby New Year"). Both are deifications of the created feature Yahuah named in Bereshit 1:14.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Daniel 7:25 — Times and Laws</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Daniyel's prophecy of a power that would "think to change times and laws." The Aramaic <em>zimnin</em> ("times") refers to Yahuah's appointed moedim; <em>dat</em> ("laws") refers to Torah. The amillennial reading identifies this power as the Roman papal system, whose calendar reforms, Sabbath change, and Torah deprecation fulfill the prophecy.</span>
    </div>
  </details>
</section>

